net.sf.mmm.util.text.api

Interface UnicodeUtil

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    UnicodeUtilImpl

    @ComponentSpecification
public interface UnicodeUtil
    This is the interface for a collection of utility functions that help with unicode characters and texts. It also contains constants for many unicode characters.
    Since:
    2.0.0
    Author:
    Joerg Hohwiller (hohwille at users.sourceforge.net)
    See Also:
    DiacriticalMark, XmlUtil.resolveEntity(String)

      • LINE_FEED

        static final char LINE_FEED
        The character indicating a move of the cursor to the next line. Originally the cursor was only moved down but remained in the same column (horizontal position). On linux/unix systems this also includes a move of the cursor to the beginning of the next line (see CARRIAGE_RETURN). This is the origin of the differences for newlines on different operating systems (windows vs. linux vs. mac).

      • LATIN_SMALL_LETTER_SCHWA

        static final char LATIN_SMALL_LETTER_SCHWA
        The small schwa letter is used in the International Phonetic Alphabet to represent the "mid central unrounded vowel". It is used for instance in the second syllable of the English word "harmony". This letter uses the same glyph as LATIN_SMALL_LETTER_TURNED_E.

      • transliterate

        String transliterate(char character)
        This method gets the transliteration of the given character.
        Parameters:
        character - is the character to convert.
        Returns:
        a sequence of characters with the transliteration of the given character or null if no such transliteration is available.
        See Also:
        Normalizer, transliterate(String)

      • transliterate

        String transliterate(String text)
        This method gets the transliteration of the given text. This method will support common transliteration standards such as ISO 843 (greek), ISO 9 (cyrillic), etc. However, for some writing systems there are multiple ways of transliteration and some things done by this method may not officially be called transliteration. So please consider it as a pragmatic way to convert text to the Latin alphabet. We are looking for help in supporting additional writing systems but not for scientific discussion about linguistic.
        Parameters:
        text - is the String to convert.
        Returns:
        the transliteration of the given text. All characters that have no transliteration will remain unmodified.
        See Also:
        Normalizer

      • normalize2Ascii

        String normalize2Ascii(char character)
        This method determines an ASCII-representation for the given character if available.
        Parameters:
        character - is the character to convert.
        Returns:
        a sequence of ASCII-characters that represent the given character or null if the character is already ASCII or there is no ASCII-representation available.
        See Also:
        Normalizer

      • normalize2Ascii

        String normalize2Ascii(CharSequence text)
        This method converts the given text to the best possible ASCII-representation. All ASCII-characters will remain unchanged. All other characters are normalized to ASCII.
        Parameters:
        text - is the text to convert.
        Returns:
        the converted text.
        See Also:
        normalize2Ascii(CharSequence, char), Normalizer

      • normalize2Ascii

        String normalize2Ascii(CharSequence text,
                       char nonNormalizableCharaterReplacement)
        This method converts the given text to the best possible ASCII-representation. All ASCII-characters will remain unchanged. All other characters are normalized to ASCII and if not possible replaced by nonNormalizableCharaterReplacement.
        Parameters:
        text - is the text to convert.
        nonNormalizableCharaterReplacement - is the character used to replace unicode characters that have no corresponding ASCII representation. Use NULL to remove these characters. A typical character to use is ?.
        Returns:
        the converted text.
        See Also:
        Normalizer
